Oh joy...Oh rapture...

I kid you not...what I found in the thrift store this morning among the
books:

title: &quot;How to cure yourself of positive thinking&quot;

by: Donald G. Smith

My copy was a paperback, copyrighted 1976, 1978 by Doanld G. Smith, and
the First Pocket Books, under the Kangaroo label, printed 1978,

ISBN 0671814230

And, it has an afterword by (Dr.) Laurence J. Peter, co-author of &quot;The
Peter Principle&quot;

For anyone who cares, I found it on Amazon.com as a used book, and for
whatever reason the hardback price was $ 0.84 and the mass market
paperback was $ 8.99. It did not show up by ISBN (I've had that happen
before) but by going to advanced search and put in the exact title and the
exact author name. I got my copy for 25 cents.

(There are other booksellers including half.com and alibris if you can't
find a copy on Amazon).

On the back of my copy is this quote:

&quot;What? You're still hung up on positive thinking? Are you fed up with the
Pollyanna claptrap of positive thinkers? Are you sick of eing told to make
lists, love your job, get involved, go along with the times......&quot;

In the front is a saying:

&quot;He who would distinguish the true from the false must have an adequate
idea of what is true and false&quot;
Spinoza

here is the &quot;Contents:

1. Good is the absence of bad
2. The negative myth
3. The semantics of the enemy
4. Resisting change
5. Dynamic negativism
6. Delusion and Fallacies
7. Tranquility
8. Pragmatic negativism
9. Everybody sing
10. Its hard to be negative

Had an postscript
afterward
index (which also has some funny entries, including comments on Norman
vincent peal, lots of defective thinking, etc).

Another book it reminds me of is &quot;The B.S. Factor&quot; by Arthur Herzog
from a similar era. BMJ would love this book. I've read some of it.
Then there is &quot;Growing up absurd&quot; by Paul Goodman

---

More later....
