1. Have at it!
2. If I see any more &quot;kindred spirit&quot; stuff, I'll dump it on SRC for y'all
to see, share, commiserate upon, etc., etc.
3. Quite a bit of the text (I read the whole book earlier) suggests that
&quot;positive attitude&quot; was being pushed pretty heavily even back
then. Nothing in the book is high level intellectual, and the
author came accross to me as being more like an &quot;Ann Landers&quot;
&quot;practical advice about social situations&quot; kind of thing and his
view about all this stuff is, I'm sorry to say, that it is quite a
bit of touchy-feelie, PC, warm-fuzzy superficial phoney crap.
4. There seems to be a wee bit of &quot;extension&quot; into the present with this
since www.despair.com is, IIRC, a modern day version of &quot;negative
attitude&quot; management advice and I've posted the &quot;demotivationals&quot;
several times (again below, too, FWIW), but the guys who came up
with them really do sell a &quot;party line&quot; line of thinking on this
stuff and they seem to get _some_ business.
5. And, FWIW, FYI, I had to work for two years with a superficial,
self-promoting, blowhard, manipulative, cheating, duplicitous
phoney back some 30 years ago and I didn't like it. There were
dozens of people around me and we all saw the same thing and we
all talked about it. Most had a dim view of the guy but their
level of outspokeness was variable. Some were really bothered by
the guy. As it turned out, the guy did do me a couple of pretty
big favors, and in the end, I did him a couple of pretty big
favors right back so I don't think either one of us owes the other
anything. And, I'm sure that a ton of this kind of quid pro quo
goes on in real life all over the world (biographies
and biographical histories often have substantial details on this)
as the &quot;high rollers&quot; play high and higher stakes with each other
and underlings haven't the faintest idea what is going on but they
are all really just playing the role of cannon fodder. I wrestle
continuously with the question of how the fight between good and
evil will end or will it just break even or even how could we
measure it (perhaps we can't and never will). All I know is that
there are a lot of authors who wrote books that attempted to
expose, correct, stop, reduce, etc., a lot of bad things or
otherwise attempted to try to make the world a better place to
live in the future. I am in favor of that. And, I wish more people
would care; too many just don't.

