I don't remember many, if any, MechE undergrads taking electromagnetic
theory.  It was mostly EE, engineering physics, and the odd
engineering major (from other areas) or two enrolled.  (The physics
folks usually enrolled in the physics department's version of the
course).

The electromagnetism course I took was the physics department's
version.  Comparing the difference between the physics and engineering
versions, they were literally 95% identical in content back when I was
an undergraduate.  The only main difference was that physics version
assumed the students already knew the math (ie. vector calculus,
ordinary + partial differential equations, etc ...), and didn't bother
to review over it again.  In the engineering version, they actually
spent the first week or two going over the math stuff like vector
calculus (ie. line + surface integrals, stokes theorem, divergence
theorem, etc ...).

Neither course covered much, if any, stuff related to design aspects.
These days the engineering version of the course is somewhat watered
down.  The physics version doesn't appear to have been significantly
watered down yet.  Though that's not to say that it will remain that
way into the near future.
